title: For Sale:  High Standard Riot Shotgun 18-7
location: Lutz/Land O' Lakes, Tampa/St. Pete, Florida
postcontent:
This is the last of my shotguns. I've been hesitant to sell it but I just don't shoot it like I used to. This is a Police model shotgun and was issued to Cook County Illinois (see pics). Serial number dates it to 1969 production. It has an 18" smooth barrel with rifle sights. The full length mag tube holds 6 rounds, 1 in the chamber makes 7 total (the designation 18-7 means 18" barrel, 7 round cap). This is by far the slickest and most accurate shotgun I've owned. The barrel is threaded to the receiver like a rifle which makes for outstanding accuracy from a smooth bore. I can make one ragged clover leaf shaped hole at 50 yds with el cheapo Wal Mart 1 oz slugs from a rest. The action is slick as snake snot. This shotgun has surprised many Ithaca snobs with it's function and accuracy. Condition wise, I would rate it 90%, none of the typical abuse you see with Police guns, just normal signs of use: the odd scratch here and there, some bluing loss on the mag tube closest the muzzle. It could use a thorough cleaning. If you're looking for a home defense powerhouse or an accurate brush buster, this is your 12ga. I am in no hurry to sell this, just looking to clear some room in the safe. My price is relatively firm so please don't waste your time sending me lowball offers. Besides, this one won't last long. Since this is my last shotgun I will throw in whatever 12ga ammo I have on hand. I know I have a couple boxes of bird shot and a handful of buck and slugs. 

The only trades I will consider would be a .22 pistol (Beretta Neos, Ruger Mark 2, Whitney Wolverine) or vintage Mossberg .22 rifles. Or quality knives (and I don't mean Gerber or Cold Steel).

title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare Winchester Model-77 .22 semi-auto rifle
postcontent:
Rare Winchester tube-fed semi-auto .22 rifle. There are a few of these floating around, but not many. They made 210,000 Winchester model 77's in the 1950's and 60's, which is quite a few.. But only 10 percent of those were tube-fed...that's 21,000. This is one of those Tube-fed models. I saw one sell on GunBroker last week for $455.00.
This one is in very good condition...very good, and it functions perfect and has every modern feature. They stopped making the Model 77 in the 1960's.
It is grooved for mounting a scope. (same size groove that is on the Ruger 10/22 and all .22 rifles). It has fully adjustable iron sites also. The bolt is on the left side, which is one of the tell-tale model 77 characteristics. It functions flawless and looks great. It will shoot cheap bulk ammo as fast as you can pull the trigger without a hiccup. This is a collector's gun BUT, it is ready to be an everyday shooter also. It looks and feels better than a Ruger. It is a Winchester, back when they were the best. It's not overly heavy and it lacks nothing that a brand new .22 rifle has. You don't feel like your holding an old outdated gun. Model number is 160694
